<html><head><title>Forms</title><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000"><h1 align="center"><font color="#990000">Forms</font></h1><p align="right"><font size="1">Last Modified   <!-- #BeginDate format:Am2 -->9/28/06<!-- #EndDate -->  </font></p><p align="center"><font size="1">  <a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149;   <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149;   <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149;   <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149;   <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149;   <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149;   <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149;   <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149;   <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149;  <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a>  </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="exform"></a>An Example Form </font></h2><p>First, let's start with an example of a form that shows you some of the basic elements of a form:</p><form name="sampleform" method="post" action="formhandler1.php">   <p><em>First, an example of a text field: </em></p>   <p>Enter your name here:       <input type="text" name="name" />    </p>   <p><em>Now, a pull-down menu:</em></p>   <p>Choose a background color:          <select name="bgcol">         <option value="#FF0000">red</option>         <option value="#00FF00">green</option>         <option value="#0000FF">blue</option>	     <option value="#000000">black</option>	     <option value="#FFFFFF">white</option>      </select>   </p>   <p><em>Now, a set of radio buttons:</em></p>   <p>Choose a text color: <br>         <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#FF0000">red</input>      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#00FF00">green</input>      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#0000FF">blue</input>      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#000000">black</input>      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#FFFFFF">white</input>   </p>    <p><em>Now, some checkboxes:</em></p>   <p>You can opt to see the hexadecimal codes for the colors you chose. Which would you like to see?         <br>      <input type="checkbox" name="showbg">background color</input>      <br>      <input type="checkbox" name="showtxt">text color</input>      </p>   <p><em>Finally, of course, a button to submit the whole thing and a button to reset... </em>         <input type="submit" name="submit_button" value="Try it out..." />       <input type="reset" name="reset_button" value="Clear it all..." />   </p></form><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="idea" id="idea"></a>The Idea </font></h2><p>A <strong>form</strong> is a part of a web page that allows you to input information to send to a web site. What you see above is an example of a form. </p><p>The form is built from several <strong>fields</strong> of different types which get the input information. As you saw above, these fields include </p><ul>  <li>text fields</li>  <li>pull-down menus </li>  <li>radio buttons</li>  <li>checkboxes</li>  <li>buttons</li>  <li>scroll boxes (not modeled above)</li></ul><p>Note the following:</p><ul>  <li>Checkboxes and radio buttons look similar, but:    <ul>      <li>Checkboxes are square, whereas radio buttons are round.</li>      <li>Checkboxes allow the user to choose any number of choices; radio buttons allow one choice. </li>    </ul>  </li>  <li>Pull-down menus and radio buttons are similar in that both are ways of choosing exactly one choice (or possibly none) from many. </li>  <li>Check boxes and scroll boxes allow the user to choose any number of choices from the set. </li></ul><p>What happens with the information you send to the form depends on the particular form. Usually, it is sent to some program on the server, which may take one of these actions: </p><ul>  <li>store the information in a file or database</li>  <li>use the information to generate a new web page (like you saw above)</li>  <li>send an email</li>  <li>any combination of the above</li></ul><p>In any case, there's something going on behind the scenes. That's called the <strong>back-end</strong> of the form. What you see and what we'll work with is called the <strong>front-end</strong>. </p><p>We'll begin with the basic code for a form, then we'll move on to how to set up each of the kinds of fields.</p><p>&nbsp; </p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="form"></a>Defining a Form </font></h2><p>Think of the <em>form</em> as a container and <em>fields</em> as what's inside that container. This analogous to a list and the list items that make up the list. </p><p>We must define the form with a set of <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;form&gt;...&lt;/form&gt;</font> tags. Between them, we must include all of the tags for the form fields. We can also include other HTML. (However, don't make your whole page a form. Just put the form tags around the fields and their labels.)</p><p>That's really all we need, although the &lt;form&gt; tag has a name attribute, which we probably ought to set. Altogether, the basic structure we'll start with looks like this: </p><table border="1" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" width="11" align="center">  <tr>    <td>      <pre><font color="#333399"><b>&lt;form name=&quot;</b></font>my_form_name<font color="#333399"><b>&quot;&gt;</b></font>   HTML for fields and labels for fields goes here<br><b><font color="#333399">&lt;/form&gt;</font></b></pre>    </td>  </tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="textbox"></a>A First Form Field: Text Boxes </font></h2><p>Each form field requires a tag (or set of tags) to insert it. Many of these form fields will be similar in that they use the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>&lt;input&gt;</strong></font> tag, but with different attributes for different kinds of fields. The text field is the first example of such a field.</p><p>As there are several different types of form fields that use the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input&gt;</font> tag, we must distinguish between them. We do this with the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">type</font> attribute. For a text field, the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">type</font> is <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">text</font>. </p><p>Every form field, regardless of its type, will require use of the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name</font> attribute. We use the name of each form field in processing the form. Because of the nature of processing, you must choose form names that do NOT include spaces. </p><p>So, a basic tag for inserting a text field looks like this:</p><p align="center"><b><font color="#330099" face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;</font></b><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name_of_the_form_field<b><font color="#330099">&quot;&gt; </font><font color="#336600"></font></b></font></p><p>In this case, no closing tag is required, so, again, this alternate tag is often used:</p><p align="center"><b><font color="#330099" face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;</font></b><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name_of_the_form_field<b><font color="#330099">&quot; /&gt; </font><font color="#336600"></font></b></font></p><p>Note that the tag does not provide any labeling for the text field. We need to use text and other tags to label clearly what we expect users to type into the text field. </p><p>&nbsp; </p><h3><font color="#990000">More Attributes</font></h3><p>We can optionally set the following two attributes for text fields:</p><ul>  <li><font color="#330099" face="Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>size</strong></font> = number of characters wide the text field is</li>  <li><strong><font color="#330099" face="Courier New, Courier, mono">maxlength</font></strong> = maximum number of characters that can be entered in the text field</li></ul><p>Note that, unlike languages like C++ and Java, we don't worry about types here. Everything is handled as text; numeric data is either recognized by the back-end form processing language or converted there. </p><p>&nbsp; </p><h3><font color="#990000">Examples</font></h3><table cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" align="center" border="1">  <tr>    <td><b><font size="-1">HTML </font></b></td>    <td><b><font size="-1">As displayed in browser</font></b></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre><b><font color="#330099">&lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;</font></b>name<b><font color="#330099">&quot; /&gt; </font><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>      <input type="text" name="name" />    </p></form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre>&lt;p&gt;Enter your name here: <font color="#336600"><b><br>   <font color="#330099">&lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;</font></b></font>name<b></b><font color="#336600"><b><font color="#330099">&quot; /&gt; </font></b></font><font color="#336600"><b><br></b></font>&lt;/p&gt;<font color="#336600"><b><br></b></font></pre>    </td>    <td>  <form> <p>Enter your name here:       <input type="text" name="name" />    </p></form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <div align="left">        <pre><b><font color="#330099">&lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;</font></b>name<b><font color="#330099">&quot; <br> size=&quot;</font></b>10<font color="#330099"><b>&quot; maxlength=&quot;</b>15<b>&quot; /&gt; </b></font></pre>    </div></td>    <td><form>       <input type="text" name="name" size="10" maxlength="15" />          </form></td>  </tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><h3><font color="#990000">Problem</font></h3><ol>  <li>Create a form field to input a person's birthday. </li>  <li>Create a set of three forms fields to input a person's birthday in parts. Label each form field and use attributes to control the length of the input. </li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="radio"></a>Radio Buttons </font></h2><p>The code for inserting radio buttons is similar to the code for text fields, in that we once again use the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input&gt;</font> tag and have the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">type</font> and <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name</font> attributes. This time, the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">type</font> is <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">radio</font>. </p><p>One new issue is the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">value</font> attribute. What you put in the form for the user to see is the front-end, but it has no meaning when the form is processed by the back-end. You need to fill in  the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">value</font> attribute with whatever value you want the field to take on for processing. This can be the same as what you should the end user or different. </p><p>The other new issue is that radio buttons travel as a group. The idea is that the user will select EXACTLY ONE option from several choices. Each radio button in the group is the same. What ties the group of radio buttons together is the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name</font> attribute. All radio buttons of the same group have the same <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name</font>. </p><p>We could add the attribute <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">checked</font> with no value (since its value is inherently &quot;true&quot;) if we'd like a particular radio button to be a default selection. </p><p>Here's the default template:</p><p align="center"><font color="#330066"><strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</font></strong></font><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name_of_the_field<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>value_sent_to_backend<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;&gt;</font></strong>What user sees as label </font></p><p>Here's the default template, acknowledging that there's no closing tag necessary: </p><p align="center"><font color="#330066"><strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</font></strong></font><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name_of_the_field<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>value_sent_to_backend<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>What user sees as label </font></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3><font color="#990000">Examples</font></h3><table cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" align="center" border="1">  <tr>    <td><b><font size="-1">HTML </font></b></td>    <td><b><font size="-1">As displayed in browser</font></b></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>txtcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>#FF0000<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>red<strong></strong><br><b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#FF0000" />        red <br>            </form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>txtcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>#FF0000<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>red<br>&lt;br&gt;<br><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>txtcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>#00FF00<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>green<br>&lt;br&gt;<br><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>txtcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>#0000FF<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>blue<br>&lt;br&gt;<br><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>txtcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>#000000<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>black<br>&lt;br&gt;<br><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>txtcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; value=&quot;</font></strong>#FFFFFF<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; checked /&gt;</font></strong>white<b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#FF0000" />red      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#00FF00" />green      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#0000FF" />blue      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#000000" />black      <br>      <input type="radio" name="txtcol" value="#FFFFFF" checked />white    </form></td>  </tr></table><h3>&nbsp;</h3><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="checkbox"></a>Checkboxes</font></h2><p>Checkboxes also use the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input&gt;</font> tag, this time with <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">type</font> attribute <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">checkbox</font>.</p><p>Checkboxes automatically get values (of &quot;on&quot; or &quot;off&quot;) attached to them when the form is submitted, so the tags for individual checkboxes are simpler than those for radio buttons. </p><p>Note that while several checkboxes might be grouped together visually on the page, there is no logical linking between checkboxes. Thus each checkbox has a different name, unlike radio buttons.</p><p>Here's the default template:</p><p align="center"><strong><font color="#330066" face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;</font></strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name_of_field<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;&gt;</font></strong>What user sees as a label </font></p><p>Here's the default template, acknowledging that there's no closing tag necessary: </p><p align="center"><strong><font color="#330066" face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;</font></strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name_of_field<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>What user sees as a label</font></p><p>&nbsp; </p><h3><font color="#990000">Examples</font></h3><table cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" align="center" border="1">  <tr>    <td><b><font size="-1">HTML </font></b></td>    <td><b><font size="-1">As displayed in browser</font></b></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre><strong><font color="#330066">&lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;</font></strong>showtxt<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong>text color<br><b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="checkbox" name="showtxt" />text color        <br>    </form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre>&lt;p&gt;You can opt to see the hexadecimal codes for the colors you chose. <br>Which would you like to see?<br>   <br>  &lt;br&gt;<b><font color="#330066"><br>  &lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;</font></b>showbg<b><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></b>background color<b><font color="#330066"><br>  &lt;br&gt;<br>  &lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;</font></b>showtxt<b><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></b>text color<b><font color="#330066"><br>   <br>&lt;/p&gt;</font><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>           <p>You can opt to see the hexadecimal codes for the colors you chose.    Which would you like to see?         <br>      <input type="checkbox" name="showbg" />background color      <br>      <input type="checkbox" name="showtxt" />text color      </p>    </form></td>  </tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><h3><font color="#990000">Problem</font></h3><ol>  <li>Create a block of HTML code for ordering a pizza. Suppose there's a deal where customers can choose any number of toppings. Create a series of checkboxes for choosing toppings. Include pepperoni, sausage, and extra cheese in your list (or more if you want).</li>  <li>Now change your code so that it is specifically for a <em>one-topping</em> pizza. </li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="button"></a>Buttons</font></h2><p>Buttons also use the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;input&gt;</font> tag. Here the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">type</font> takes on different values depending on the type of button:</p><ul>  <li><strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">submit</font></strong> is used for buttons that send in the form</li>  <li><strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">reset</font></strong> is used for buttons that clear the contents of fields or reset them to default values</li></ul><p>Additionally, the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">value</font> attribute must be set. In this case the value DOES show up on screen. It is also sent to the form's back-end. For back-end processing when you have multiple submit buttons, there may be specific <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">value</font>s you want. </p><p>Finally, the name attribute behaves like before. </p><h3><font color="#990000">Examples</font></h3><table cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" align="center" border="1">  <tr>    <td><b><font size="-1">HTML </font></b></td>    <td><b><font size="-1">As displayed in browser</font></b></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td><pre><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>submit_button<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;</font></strong><font color="#330066"><strong> value=&quot;</strong></font>Try it out...<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong> <br><b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="submit" value="Try it out..." />        <br>    </form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td><pre><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>submit_button<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;</font></strong><font color="#330066"><strong> </strong></font><font color="#330066"><strong>value=&quot;</strong></font>OK<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong> <b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="submit" value="OK" />    </form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td><pre><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>submit_button<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;</font></strong><font color="#330066"><strong> </strong></font><font color="#330066"><strong>value=&quot;</strong></font>Search<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong> <b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="submit" value="Search" />    </form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td><pre><font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;input type=&quot;reset&quot; name=&quot;</strong></font>reset_button<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;</font></strong><font color="#330066"><strong> </strong></font><font color="#330066"><strong>value=&quot;</strong></font>Cancel<strong><font color="#330066">&quot; /&gt;</font></strong> <b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>        <input type="reset" value="Cancel" />    </form></td>  </tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="pulldown"></a>Pull-Down Menus (and Scroll Boxes) </font></h2><p>Here's another case of hierarchy in HTML. Again, think back to how we did lists: tags to start and stop the list wrapping tags to start and stop each list item. </p><p>For pull-down menus, the idea is similar. We need a set of tags to start and stop the pull-down menus. Inside these tags, we need pairs of tags for each option we want to include in the menu.</p><p>The pull-down menu itself is created with the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;select&gt;</font> tag. It requires the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">name</font> attribute to be set. </p><p>Each option in the list is created with the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;option&gt;</font> tag. Each option needs to have the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">value</font> attribute set. The text that shows up in the menu is given between the opening and closing <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;option&gt;</font> tags. Here's a general form:</p><p align="center"><strong><font color="#330066" face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;option value=&quot;</font></strong><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">what_is_sent_to_backend<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;&gt;</font></strong>What user sees in menu<font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;/option&gt;</strong></font></font></p><p>Like radio buttons, a pull-down menu allows the user to choose exactly one option from several. However, it is possible to turn a pull-down menu into a scroll box, which lets user choose several options (using Apple, Ctrl, or Shift). Do this by including the attribute <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">multiple</font> (with no value -- it's &quot;true&quot; if it's there). </p><p>&nbsp; </p><h3><font color="#990000">Examples</font></h3><table cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" align="center" border="1">  <tr>    <td><b><font size="-1">HTML </font></b></td>    <td><b><font size="-1">As displayed in browser</font></b></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre><strong><font color="#330066">&lt;select name=&quot;</font></strong>bgcol<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;</font></strong>#FF0000<strong><font color="#330066">&quot;&gt;</font></strong>red<font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;</strong></font>#00FF00<font color="#330066"><strong>&quot;&gt;</strong></font>green<font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;</strong></font>#0000FF<font color="#330066"><strong>&quot;&gt;</strong></font>blue<font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;</strong></font>#000000<font color="#330066"><strong>&quot;&gt;</strong></font>black<font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;</strong></font>#FFFFFF<font color="#330066"><strong>&quot;&gt;</strong></font>white<font color="#330066"><strong>&lt;/option&gt;<br>&lt;/select&gt;<br></strong></font><b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td><form>             <select name="bgcol">         <option value="#FF0000">red</option>         <option value="#00FF00">green</option>         <option value="#0000FF">blue</option>         <option value="#000000">black</option>         <option value="#FFFFFF">white</option>      </select><br>    </form></td>  </tr>  <tr>    <td>      <pre>&lt;select name=&quot;bgcol&quot; <font color="#330066"><strong>multiple</strong></font>&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;#FF0000&quot;&gt;red&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;#00FF00&quot;&gt;green&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;blue&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;#000000&quot;&gt;black&lt;/option&gt;<br>   &lt;option value=&quot;#FFFFFF&quot;&gt;white&lt;/option&gt;<br>&lt;/select&gt;<b><font color="#336600"><br></font></b></pre>    </td>    <td>	<form>      	 <select name="bgcol" multiple>         <option value="#FF0000">red</option>         <option value="#00FF00">green</option>         <option value="#0000FF">blue</option>         <option value="#000000">black</option>         <option value="#FFFFFF">white</option>      </select>    </form>   </td>  </tr></table><h3><font color="#990000">Problem</font></h3><ol>  <li>Implement the pizza topping choice from the last problem with a pull-down menu. </li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="backend"></a>The Back End </font></h2><p>How exactly the back end of a form works could be several courses, and we won't cover it here. We'll just scratch the surface. </p><p>There are a few attributes of the <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;form&gt;</font> tag that specify what happens when users submit the form:</p><ul>  <li><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">method</font> tells how the information in the form is sent to the server, either <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&quot;post&quot;</font> or <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&quot;get&quot;</font> (usually depending on the language of the form handler).</li>  <li><font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">action</font> tells where the script that handles the form is located. </li></ul><p>The back end is usually written using Perl, where information is submitted via <em>common gateway interface</em> or <em>cgi</em>, or, more increasingly today, in PHP. Many other technologies may be involved. For example, JavaScript is frequently used to <strong>validate</strong> the form, or check that inputs are reasonable before submitting the form. If the form searches a database or stores information in a database, a database query language like SQL will also be part of the mix. </p><p>Here's an example of the form tag for the form I gave you at the top of these notes:</p><p align="center"> <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono">&lt;form name=&quot;sampleform&quot; method=&quot;post&quot; action=&quot;formhandler1.php&quot;&gt; </font> </p><p><font size="-1">(For the curious, <a href="formhandler1-php.txt" target="_blank"  >here's the PHP code</a> that is the missing link. Most of the time, this back-end is NOT made available to the end user.)</font></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p><hr><h2><font color="#990000"><a name="completeex"></a>Putting it All Together </font></h2><p>Here's the complete code for the form we saw at the beginning of this page:</p><table border="1" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" width="11" align="center">  <tr>    <td>      <pre>&lt;form name=&quot;sampleform&quot; method=&quot;post&quot; action=&quot;formhandler1.php&quot;&gt;      &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;First, an example of a text field: &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;<br>   &lt;p&gt;Enter your name here: <br>       &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;name&quot; /&gt; <br>   &lt;/p&gt;<p>   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Now, a pull-down menu:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;<br>   &lt;p&gt;Choose a background color: <br>      &lt;select name=&quot;bgcol&quot;&gt;<br>        &lt;option value=&quot;#FF0000&quot;&gt;red&lt;/option&gt;<br>        &lt;option value=&quot;#00FF00&quot;&gt;green&lt;/option&gt;        &lt;option value=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;blue&lt;/option&gt;        &lt;option value=&quot;#000000&quot;&gt;black&lt;/option&gt;        &lt;option value=&quot;#FFFFFF&quot;&gt;white&lt;/option&gt;<br>      &lt;/select&gt;   &lt;/p&gt;      &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Now, a set of radio buttons:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>   &lt;p&gt;Choose a text color: &lt;br&gt;<br>      &lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;txtcol&quot; value=&quot;#FF0000&quot; /&gt;red<br>      &lt;br&gt;      &lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;txtcol&quot; value=&quot;#00FF00&quot; /&gt;green      &lt;br&gt;      &lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;txtcol&quot; value=&quot;#0000FF&quot; /&gt;blue<br>      &lt;br&gt;        &lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;txtcol&quot; value=&quot;#000000&quot; /&gt;black      &lt;br&gt;<br>      &lt;input type=&quot;radio&quot; name=&quot;txtcol&quot; value=&quot;#FFFFFF&quot; /&gt;white<br>   &lt;/p&gt;<br>   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Now, some checkboxes:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;<br>   &lt;p&gt;You can opt to see the hexadecimal codes for the colors you chose. <br>   Which would you like to see?       &lt;br&gt;<br>      &lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;showbg&quot;&gt;background color&lt;/input&gt;      &lt;br&gt;<br>      &lt;input type=&quot;checkbox&quot; name=&quot;showtxt&quot;&gt;text color&lt;/input&gt;      &lt;/p&gt;      &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Finally, of course, a button to submit the whole thing and a<br>   button to reset... &lt;/em&gt;      &lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;submit_button&quot; value=&quot;Try it out...&quot; /&gt; <br>      &lt;input type=&quot;reset&quot; name=&quot;reset_button&quot; value=&quot;Clear it all...&quot; /&gt;   &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/form&gt;</pre>    </td>  </tr></table><pre>&nbsp;</pre><p>&nbsp;</p><p align="center"><font size="1"><a href="#exform">Example</a> &#149; <a href="#idea">The Idea</a> &#149; <a href="#form">Form Tag</a> &#149; <a href="#textbox">Text Boxes</a> &#149; <a href="#radio">Radio Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#checkbox">Checkboxes</a> &#149; <a href="#button">Buttons</a> &#149; <a href="#pulldown">Pull-Down Menus</a> &#149; <a href="#backend">Back End</a> &#149; <a href="#completeex">Complete Form Code</a> </font></p></body></html>